<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1167793912012">
<term>directional derivative</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167793912017">the derivative of a function in the direction of a given unit vector</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1167793912021">
<term>gradient</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167793912027">the gradient of the function <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is defined to be <m:math><m:mrow><m:mo>∇</m:mo><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>∂</m:mo><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mtext>/</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mo>∂</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>∂</m:mo><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mtext>/</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mo>∂</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>j</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> which can be generalized to a function of any number of independent variables</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
